When you are using an `if` statement remember this -&gt;

`if` - Executes the body if the parameters return true.

`else if` - Executes the body if the parameters return true and the previous `if`/`else if` statement was false.

`else` - Executes the body if all the previous `if` statements return false.

Each `if` statement can get continued by an `else`/`else if` statement which I call a chain. When you create a new `if` statement then the previous chain is ended. Which means if you write another `if` statement and write and `else` it will only run based on which chain it is.

**So what is the mistake you are making?** Well take a look at your if statements
```
if(age&gt;=18) {
	System.out.println(&quot;Qualified for DL&quot;);
}

if((age&gt;=22) &amp;&amp; (age&lt;=60)) {
	System.out.println(&quot;Working individuals&quot;);
}

else {
	System.out.println(&quot;Disqualified&quot;);
}
```
The first `if` statement runs as usual so it moves on to the second `if` statement. Now using what we had learned earlier we can see that the `else` statement runs when `if((age&gt;=22) &amp;&amp; (age&lt;=60))` is false because it is in it&#39;s chain. In your case, 21 is less that 22 so that statement is false, which means it runs the `else` statement

**How can you fix this problem?**
Change the second `if` statement into and `else if`. Here&#39;s the fixed code
```
if(age&gt;=18) {
	System.out.println(&quot;Qualified for DL&quot;);
}

else if((age&gt;=22) &amp;&amp; (age&lt;=60)) {
	System.out.println(&quot;Working individuals&quot;);
}

else {
	System.out.println(&quot;Disqualified&quot;);
}
```

